":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotland"},"nl":{"1212–1263":"1212–1263","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1241–Male":"1241–Overleden","1243–Male":"1243–Overleden","1244–Female":"1244–Overleden","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1263":"1263","1241":"1241","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1241":"circa 1241","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","Abt 1243":"circa 1243","1244":"1244","Between 1219 and 1273":"van 1219 to 1273","1243":"1243","1210":"1210","Annandale Dumfries Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dundaff Castle, Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland"},"en":{"1212–1263":"1212–1263","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1241–Male":"1241–Deceased","1243–Male":"1243–Deceased","1244–Female":"1244–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1263":"1263","1241":"1241","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1241":"about 1241","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","Abt 1243":"about 1243","1244":"1244","Between 1219 and 1273":"from 1219 to 1273","1243":"1243","1210":"1210","Annandale Dumfries Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dundaff Castle, Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sinclair","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Saint-Clair-sur-Elle (Manche), so called from the dedication of its church to Saint Clarus (see   Clare   3).","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname.","History: The Scottish family <i>Sinclair</i> (see 1 above) came to southern Scotland in the twelfth century from Huntingdonshire with the de Morvilles. Descendants of these Sinclairs became earls of Caithness in the 15th century. The frequency of the surname in Caithness and Orkney is largely due to the adoption by tenants of the name of their overlord."],"variants":[{"name":"Clare","meanings":["Irish (Clare, Wicklow, and Wexford): habitational name from Clare in Suffolk (an eastern county of England), the center of a major Norman baronial estate since the Norman Conquest. The English placename probably originated as a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright, gentle, or warm’. The surname is not from the Irish county name <i>Clare</i>, which is either from the surname or from a place called with Gaelic <i>clár</i> ‘plank bridge’. Another Norman surname in the southeast of Ireland was <i>de Clere</i>, from Clères in Seine-Maritime (France), named from the local river.","English and French: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Cla(i)re</i> (from Latin <i>Clara</i>, from <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright, famous’) which achieved some popularity, greater elsewhere in Europe than in England, through the fame of Saint Clare of Assisi (see   Chiara  ). The English surname seems to have been interchangeable with   Clear   1.","English: occupational name from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cley</i> ‘clay’. The work of medieval clayers involved plastering a framework of interwoven twigs with mud to produce wattle-and-daub work."]},{"name":"St. Clair","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Sinclair  . This is also a French Canadian and American French altered form of the same surname.","French (<b>Saint-Clair</b>): habitational name from any of several places, e.g. in Normandy, named Saint-Clair (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Clarus). Compare   Saintclair  .","Haitian (also <b>Saint-Clair</b>): ornamental name or nickname, perhaps ironic, composed of French <i>saint</i> ‘saint’ or ‘holy’ and <i>clair</i> ‘clear’ or ‘lightness’. Alternatively, perhaps of the same French origin as 2 above. Compare   Saintclair  ."]}]},{"name":"Annabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Sometimes taken as an elaboration of   Anna  , but more probably a dissimilated form of   Amabel .  It has been common in Scotland since the 12th century and was still in use in England in the 1600s. Its recent revival in popularity in England and elsewhere dates from the 1940s."],"variants":[{"name":"Annabell","meanings":["Sometimes taken as an elaboration of   Anna  , but more probably a dissimilated form of   Amabel .  It has been common in Scotland since the 12th century and was still in use in England in the 1600s. Its recent revival in popularity in England and elsewhere dates from the 1940s."]},{"name":"Annabella","meanings":["Sometimes taken as an elaboration of   Anna  , but more probably a dissimilated form of   Amabel .  It has been common in Scotland since the 12th century and was still in use in England in the 1600s. Its recent revival in popularity in England and elsewhere dates from the 1940s."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Annabelle Sinclair was born in 1212, in Perthshire, Scotland. She married Sir David Graham - Laird Of Dundaff in 1240, in Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1263, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1212–1263":"1212–1263","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1241–Male":"1241–Surnud","1243–Male":"1243–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1263":"1263","1241":"1241","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1241":"umbes 1241","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","Abt 1243":"umbes 1243","1244":"1244","Between 1219 and 1273":"1219